I want to create an emulator (for personal use) for an old MMO game that&#39;s not here anymore.

I figured out how the packets work, but I need a way to parse them easily and was wondering if it&#39;s a common practice and if there&#39;s maybe some library for it already.

It goes like this:

- Packets are essentially structs.
- The packet begins with X amount of bits (rounded up to 8) that represent which fields are contained in the packet, in order. X being the amount of fields in the struct.
- Following are bytes representing the struct fields. Some are a direct value, some are more complicated like dynamically sized buffers or sub-packets.

So, as an example:

    struct FooPacket {
        uint32 a;
        uint32 b;
        uint32 c;
    }

    // 1st and 2nd bits are set, so this packet only contains the a and b fields:
    03,
    // The a field:
    AA, AA, AA, AA,
    // The b field:
    BB, BB, BB, BB

So... is that a common practice for game servers, and are there any libraries for this type of communication?

If not, what would be the easiest way to do it and in what programming language?

C/C++ don&#39;t seem to be a good option here because of lack of reflection (or clean way of reflection for that matter, I&#39;m aware of libraries like boost::pfr).

Storing RTTI for every single packet by hand doesn&#39;t seem too fun either,
there are hundreds of possible packet structs like this.

